who had given him a good education, and being lest destitute, became an apparitor to the magistrates in his native town. He asterwards served in the army, and then re- turned home and taught. In his fiftieth year (A.u.c. 691) he came to Rome and set up a school, which brought him more fame than profit. He wrote a book on the ill- treatment that teachers experienced from the parents of their pupils. Perhaps they had reason to find fault with him if Horace's epithet gives a right notion of his character. He seems to have held the rod as the prin- ciple os school government3 wherefore the following line was written on him by one Domitius Marsus, “ Si quos Orbilius ferula seuumque cecidit.” He lived in great poverty in a garret (see Epp. i. l.9l,n.) to nearly a hundred years of age, having long lost his manui-y. His townspeople were proud of him, and -erected a marble statue to his memory. These particulars are from Sue- tonius’ account of Orbilius in his treatise De Illustr. Grammaticis, c. 9. Orbilius was in his sorty-eighth year when Horace was born. He was therefore not young when the poet went to his school. Per- haps Horace's judgment of Livius may have been influenced by his early recollections, aud “ what it then detested still abhorred,'' as a modern poet has said of Horace him- self, “the drill'd dull lesson forced down word by word.''
